"English: habitational name from any of the three places called Edington in Northumberland, Somerset, and Wiltshire, or from Eddington, Berkshire. Edington in Northumberland arises from Old English <i>Idingtūn</i>, from the Old English personal name <i>Ida</i>, + <i>ing</i>, denoting association, + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’ (compare   Ida  ). In Somerset, the name comes either from the Old English male name <i>Ēadwine</i> or from the feminine <i>Ēadwynn</i> + <i>ing</i> + <i>tūn</i>. Edington (Wiltshire) is from either the Old English personal name <i>Ētha</i> + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’, or from Old English <i>ēthe</i> ‘uncultivated’ + <i>dūn</i>."]}]},{"name":"Fulcher","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly East Anglia): from the Middle English personal name <i>Fulcher</i>, <i>Fulchier</i>, <i>Fulger</i>, <i>Fulker</i>, <i>Foucher</i>, a name of Norman introduction, from an Old French form of ancient Germanic <i>Fulchar</i>, <i>Fulcher</i>. Old English <i>Folchere</i> (not recorded after 824) and Old Danish <i>Folkar</i> (otherwise unrecorded in England) are alternative, but unlikely sources of the surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Fudge","meanings":["Generally, no doubt, a transferred use of the surname, rather than a coinage with direct reference to the legal officer (Old French <i>juge</i>, from Latin <i>iudex</i>). As a Jewish name it represents a translation of the Hebrew name <i>Dayan</i>, which denotes a rabbinic judge."]},{"name":"Folger","meanings":["From an Old Norse personal name from <i>hólmr</i> ‘island’ + <i>geirr</i> ‘spear’. It was borne by one of Charlemagne's generals, known in English as ‘Ogier the Dane’."]},{"name":"Foulger","meanings":["English: variant of   Fulcher  ."]},{"name":"Folker","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Volker ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":15,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1